concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
use lld instead of GNU ld for linking the fuzzers

The fuzzers link a huge number of symbols (each fuzzer is ~43MB as of
this writing) and GNU ld is wildly slower at this. This change lowers
the build time for all fuzzers by 50% on a 22 core machine.

concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
== is not a valid comparison for char * in C

This worked anyway since the compiler unified the macro and the string
literal so it compared two identical addresses, but we should do the
comparison correctly.

These commands fail:

```
$ magick logo: -type truecolor logo.qoi
$ magick logo.qoi logo.pnm
magick: unexpected end-of-file 'logo.qoi': Invalid argument @ error/qoi.c/ReadQOIImage/266.
```

concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
Remove unused EXPLICIT_TEMPLATE_INSTANTIATION

The code is commented out. In addition, std::vector<const T> is
undefined in C++ because std::allocator<const T> is undefined
([allocator.requirements.general] says that T is any cv-unqualified
object type). libstdc++ seems to never allow std::vector<const T>
(https://gcc.gnu.org/bugzilla/show_bug.cgi?id=48101).

message:
Is it possible to add an image that demonstrates this issue? 

And why do we need the changes to `GetFITSPixel`? Could we not do these checks in the `for` loop instead? And when you don't read the first pixel but set it to `DBL_MAX` and `DBL_MIN` the for loop should start at `0` instead.

concept:name: IssueComment
message:
I put the changes in GetFITSPixel since it is called later when setting pixel data on the Image object, and I wanted to include the NaN->0 there too.

You're right, the loop should start at 0, I'll patch that.

Here is a demonstration, pre-change:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/94071409/165176829-1f222b25-d5de-42fa-8080-b0ba3f1f8bd2.png)

After patch:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/94071409/165176975-d2fdce77-efe1-49f2-a8db-dc9c54c6f92a.png)

Here's the fits file I'm testing with (zipped so I can attach it here) [211_to_304.fits.zip](https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/files/8558060/211_to_304.fits.zip)
It was generated with [sunpy](https://docs.sunpy.org/en/stable/generated/gallery/map_transformations/reprojection_different_observers.html)

concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
The effect of modulate:colorspace LCH is different for palette and truecolor images.

- Palette image modulate LCH as LCHab.   ( OK )
  - ImageMagick LCH colorscape alias to LCHab since v6.8.5-5
- Truecolor image modulate LCH as LCHuv. ( NG )
  - Documented behavior. but old.

-define modulate:colorspace=LCH -modulate <TrueColor Image>, the actual colorspace is changed from LCHuv to LCHab.

concept:name: IssueComment
message:
If the LCH colorspace is to be unified with LCHab alias, this comment should also be modified.

https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/blob/7.1.0-46/MagickCore/accelerate-kernels-private.h#L72

```
  LCHColorspace,           /* alias for LCHuv */
```

concept:name: IssueCommentSupplement
message:
Err… Fellows, years are passing by as well as issues about Unicode, but
on Windows we still have the following anomaly:
```console
$ magick convert -monitor C:\Квартира\комната.jpg out.pdf
load image[C:\╨Ъ╨▓╨░╤А╤В╨╕╤А╨░\╨║╨╛╨╝╨╜╨░╤В╨░.jpg]: 1279 of 1280, 100% complete
...
```
Any chance to fix that?

concept:name: IssueCommentSupplement
message:
@fmw42, not sure what I should grasp from that very long page. I have lots of modern command-line tools (ffmpeg, ripgrep, curl to name a few) which output non-Latin symbols correctly, without giving them a gibberish look. So it's possible.

E.g.
```console
$ ffmpeg -i C:\Квартира\комната.jpg out.png
Input #0, image2, from 'C:\Квартира\комната.jpg':
...
```

Question is when will ImageMagick join the club?

concept:name: IssueCommentSupplement
message: Type the symbols using a UTF-8 compatible text editor or type them into a UTF-8 compatible text file and then put the text file into the place for the text as @textfile.txt. See example shown on that page. The important thing is that the editor or file must be UTF-compatible

concept:name: IssueCommentSupplement
message: The progress monitor directly takes the image filename and prints it.  That works fine for UTF-8, but if its a wide-character stream it does not print properly under Windows.  ImageMagick honors UTF-8 encoding by default.  It tries to makes accommodations, where possible, for wide-characters.  We'll investigate and try to commit a patch once we find a proper solution to the issue.

concept:name: IssueCommentSupplement
message:
@fmw42, I'm talking not about producing an image with Unicode symbols, but about the distorted look of paths and filenames while ImageMagick process them.

To reproduce the issue, 
- create a folder with Cyrillic (Russian) letters `C:\Квартира`
- place some image there named `комната.jpg`
- run a regular Windows shell `cmd.exe` in that folder ([like this](https://superuser.com/a/340051))
- run `magick.exe convert -monitor C:\Квартира\комната.jpg out.pdf`

![2022-12-24T1128 imagemagick unicode bug 01](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/373718/209428672-5c0898f4-a3e0-416e-ac6c-4927f4895da6.png)

Then you'll see that processing goes fine except that path and filenames are turned into `╨Ъ╨▓╨░╤А╤В╨╕╤А╨░\╨║╨╛╨╝╨╜╨░╤В╨░.jpg` in the command output, whereas `C:\Квартира\комната.jpg` is expected as typed above.

Luckily, there is a workaround, which includes running `chcp 65001` to change shell's codepage (from default 866 in my case) before the processing begins. Then paths look fine in ImagickMagick's output. But it's not required in case of [aforementioned](https://github.com/ImageMagick/ImageMagick/pull/5713#issuecomment-1364435140) ffmpeg and many other utils.

![2022-12-24T1151 imagemagick unicode bug 02](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/373718/209428367-ba6e101d-8dfb-4d5f-8e59-9a98da094481.png)

concept:name: SubmitCommit
message:
Chrome, Mozilla, GIMP do not assume sRGB

I think it was misworded, 2.2 gAMA should be deleted,
cause it is mandatery in the case sRGB chunk is included,
but does not mean sRGB if sRGB chunk is absent. It means
pure 2.2 gamma. Doc part of #4375.

Reference: PNG spec. about fallback for sRGB chunk.
